50 // allocsize has two integer arguments, but because they're both 32 bits, we can ----
51 // pack them into one 64-bit value, at the cost of making said value ----
52 // nonsensical. ----
53 // ----
54 // In order to do this, we need to reserve one value of the second (optional) ----
55 // allocsize argument to signify "not present." ----
56 static const unsigned AllocSizeNumElemsNotPresent = -1; ----
57 ----
58 static uint64_t packAllocSizeArgs(unsigned ElemSizeArg, 0
59 const std::optional &NumElemsArg) { ----
60 assert((!NumElemsArg || *NumElemsArg != AllocSizeNumElemsNotPresent) && 0
61 "Attempting to pack a reserved value"); ----
62 ----
63 return uint64_t(ElemSizeArg) << 32 | 0
64 NumElemsArg.value_or(AllocSizeNumElemsNotPresent); 0
65 } ----
66 ----
67 static std::pair> ----
68 unpackAllocSizeArgs(uint64_t Num) { 0
69 unsigned NumElems = Num & std::numeric_limits::max(); 0
70 unsigned ElemSizeArg = Num >> 32; 0
71 ----
72 std::optional NumElemsArg; 0
73 if (NumElems != AllocSizeNumElemsNotPresent) 0
74 NumElemsArg = NumElems; 0
75 return std::make_pair(ElemSizeArg, NumElemsArg); 0
76 } ----
77 ----
78 static uint64_t packVScaleRangeArgs(unsigned MinValue, 0
79 std::optional MaxValue) { ----
80 return uint64_t(MinValue) << 32 | MaxValue.value_or(0); 0
81 } ----
82 ----
83 static std::pair> ----
84 unpackVScaleRangeArgs(uint64_t Value) { 0
85 unsigned MaxValue = Value & std::numeric_limits::max(); 0
86 unsigned MinValue = Value >> 32; 0
87 ----
88 return std::make_pair(MinValue, 0
89 MaxValue > 0 ? MaxValue : std::optional()); 0
90 } ----

565 // Convert target-dependent attributes to strings of the form: ----
566 // ----

577 // printable, those have to be escaped to make the attribute value ----
578 // printable as is. e.g. "\01__gnu_mcount_nc" ----

580 if (!AttrVal.empty()) { 0

1161 AttributeList::get(LLVMContext &C, 0
1162 ArrayRef> Attrs) { ----
1163 // If there are no attributes then return a null AttributesList pointer. ----
1164 if (Attrs.empty()) 0
1165 return {}; 0
1166 ----
1167 assert(llvm::is_sorted(Attrs, llvm::less_first()) && 0
1168 "Misordered Attributes list!"); ----

1170 [](const std::pair &Pair) { ----
1171 return Pair.second.isValid(); ----
1172 }) && ----
1173 "Pointless attribute!"); ----
1174 ----
1175 // Create a vector if (unsigned, AttributeSetNode*) pairs from the attributes ----
1176 // list. ----
1177 SmallVector, 8> AttrPairVec; 0
1178 for (ArrayRef>::iterator I = Attrs.begin(), 0
1179 E = Attrs.end(); I != E; ) { 0
1180 unsigned Index = I->first; 0
1181 SmallVector AttrVec; 0
1182 while (I != E && I->first == Index) { 0
1183 AttrVec.push_back(I->second); 0
1184 ++I; 0
1185 } ----
1186 ----
1187 AttrPairVec.emplace_back(Index, AttributeSet::get(C, AttrVec)); 0
1188 } 0
1189 ----
1190 return get(C, AttrPairVec); 0
1191 } 0

1238 NumSets = 2; 0

1685 /// Attribute comparator that only compares attribute keys. Enum attributes are ----
1686 /// sorted before string attributes. ----
1687 struct AttributeComparator { ----
1688 bool operator()(Attribute A0, Attribute A1) const { ----
1689 bool A0IsString = A0.isStringAttribute(); ----
1690 bool A1IsString = A1.isStringAttribute(); ----
1691 if (A0IsString) { ----
1692 if (A1IsString) ----
1693 return A0.getKindAsString() < A1.getKindAsString(); ----
1694 else ----
1695 return false; ----
1696 } ----
1697 if (A1IsString) ----
1698 return true; ----
1699 return A0.getKindAsEnum() < A1.getKindAsEnum(); ----
1700 } ----
1701 bool operator()(Attribute A0, Attribute::AttrKind Kind) const { 59 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1702 if (A0.isStringAttribute()) 59 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1703 return false; 4 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1704 return A0.getKindAsEnum() < Kind; 55 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1705 } ----
1706 bool operator()(Attribute A0, StringRef Kind) const { 88 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1707 if (A0.isStringAttribute()) 88 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1708 return A0.getKindAsString() < Kind; 56 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1709 return true; 32 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1710 } ----
1711 }; ----

1942 /// Which attributes cannot be applied to a type. ----
1943 AttributeMask AttributeFuncs::typeIncompatible(Type *Ty, 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1944 AttributeSafetyKind ASK) { ----
1945 AttributeMask Incompatible; 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1946 ----
1947 if (!Ty->isIntegerTy()) { 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1948 // Attributes that only apply to integers. ----
1949 if (ASK & ASK_SAFE_TO_DROP) 0
1950 Incompatible.addAttribute(Attribute::AllocAlign); 0
1951 if (ASK & ASK_UNSAFE_TO_DROP) 0
1952 Incompatible.addAttribute(Attribute::SExt).addAttribute(Attribute::ZExt); 0
1953 } ----
1954 ----
1955 if (!Ty->isPointerTy()) { 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1956 // Attributes that only apply to pointers. ----
1957 if (ASK & ASK_SAFE_TO_DROP) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1958 Incompatible.addAttribute(Attribute::NoAlias) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1959 .addAttribute(Attribute::NoCapture) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1960 .addAttribute(Attribute::NonNull) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1961 .addAttribute(Attribute::ReadNone) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1962 .addAttribute(Attribute::ReadOnly) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1963 .addAttribute(Attribute::Dereferenceable) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1964 .addAttribute(Attribute::DereferenceableOrNull); 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1965 if (ASK & ASK_UNSAFE_TO_DROP) 14 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

2005 /// Callees with dynamic denormal modes are compatible with any caller mode. ----
2006 static bool denormModeCompatible(DenormalMode CallerMode, 0
2007 DenormalMode CalleeMode) { ----
2008 if (CallerMode == CalleeMode || CalleeMode == DenormalMode::getDynamic()) 0
2009 return true; 0
2010 ----
2011 // If they don't exactly match, it's OK if the mismatched component is ----
2012 // dynamic. ----
2013 if (CalleeMode.Input == CallerMode.Input && 0
2014 CalleeMode.Output == DenormalMode::Dynamic) 0
2015 return true; 0
2016 ----
2017 if (CalleeMode.Output == CallerMode.Output && 0
2018 CalleeMode.Input == DenormalMode::Dynamic) 0
2019 return true; 0
2020 return false; 0
2021 } ----

2037 return false; 0

2070 /// If the inlined function had a higher stack protection level than the ----
2071 /// calling function, then bump up the caller's stack protection level. ----
2072 static void adjustCallerSSPLevel(Function &Caller, const Function &Callee) { 0
2073 // If the calling function has *no* stack protection level (e.g. it was built ----
2074 // with Clang's -fno-stack-protector or no_stack_protector attribute), don't ----
2075 // change it as that could change the program's semantics. ----
2076 if (!Caller.hasStackProtectorFnAttr()) 0
2077 return; 0
2078 ----
2079 // If upgrading the SSP attribute, clear out the old SSP Attributes first. ----
2080 // Having multiple SSP attributes doesn't actually hurt, but it adds useless ----
2081 // clutter to the IR. ----
2082 AttributeMask OldSSPAttr; 0
2083 OldSSPAttr.addAttribute(Attribute::StackProtect) 0
2084 .addAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectStrong) 0
2085 .addAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectReq); 0
2086 ----
2087 if (Callee.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectReq)) { 0
2088 Caller.removeFnAttrs(OldSSPAttr); 0
2089 Caller.addFnAttr(Attribute::StackProtectReq); 0
2090 } else if (Callee.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectStrong) && 0
2091 !Caller.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectReq)) { 0
2092 Caller.removeFnAttrs(OldSSPAttr); 0
2093 Caller.addFnAttr(Attribute::StackProtectStrong); 0
2094 } else if (Callee.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtect) && 0
2095 !Caller.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectReq) && 0
2096 !Caller.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::StackProtectStrong)) 0
2097 Caller.addFnAttr(Attribute::StackProtect); 0
2098 } 0

2131 /// If the inlined function defines a min legal vector width, then ensure ----
2132 /// the calling function has the same or larger min legal vector width. If the ----
2133 /// caller has the attribute, but the callee doesn't, we need to remove the ----
2134 /// attribute from the caller since we can't make any guarantees about the ----
2135 /// caller's requirements. ----
2136 /// This function is called after the inlining decision has been made so we have ----
2137 /// to merge the attribute this way. Heuristics that would use ----
2138 /// min-legal-vector-width to determine inline compatibility would need to be ----
2139 /// handled as part of inline cost analysis. ----
2140 static void ----
2141 adjustMinLegalVectorWidth(Function &Caller, const Function &Callee) { 0

2144 Attribute CalleeAttr = Callee.getFnAttribute("min-legal-vector-width"); 0
2145 if (CalleeAttr.isValid()) { 0
2146 uint64_t CallerVectorWidth, CalleeVectorWidth; ----
2147 CallerAttr.getValueAsString().getAsInteger(0, CallerVectorWidth); 0
2148 CalleeAttr.getValueAsString().getAsInteger(0, CalleeVectorWidth); 0
2149 if (CallerVectorWidth < CalleeVectorWidth) 0
2150 Caller.addFnAttr(CalleeAttr); 0
2151 } else { ----
2152 // If the callee doesn't have the attribute then we don't know anything ----
2153 // and must drop the attribute from the caller. ----
2154 Caller.removeFnAttr("min-legal-vector-width"); 0
2155 } ----
2156 } ----

1693 return A0.getKindAsString() < A1.getKindAsString(); 1693 return A0.getKindAsString() < A1.getKindAsString();
1694 else 1694 else
1695 return false; 1695 return false;
1696 } 1696 }
1697 if (A1IsString) 1697 if (A1IsString)
1698 return true; 1698 return true;
1699 return A0.getKindAsEnum() < A1.getKindAsEnum(); 1699 return A0.getKindAsEnum() < A1.getKindAsEnum();
1700 } 1700 }
